{"accepted":[{"assertion":"Formal-Conjectures statement: Erdos456.erdos_456.parts.ii https://google-deepmind.github.io/formal-conjectures/theorem/?name=Erdos456.erdos_456.parts.ii.","id":"vf_124f1d0f80706e80","trust":"signed","type":"theoretical"},{"assertion":"Erdős Problem #456: declared status 'open'. Formalized: yes. Let $p_n$ be the smallest prime $\\equiv 1\\pmod{n}$ and let $m_n$ be the smallest integer such that $n\\mid \\phi(m_n)$.\n\nIs it true that $m_n<p_n$ for almost all $n$? Does $p_n/m_n\\to \\infty$ for almost all $n$? Are there infinitely many primes $p$ such that $p-1$ is the only $n$ for which $m_n=p$? Current best: Linnik's theorem implies that $p_n\\leq n^{O(1)}$. It is trivial that $m_n\\leq p_n$ always. van Doorn in the comments has noted that if $n=2^{2k+1}$ then $m_n\\leq 2n$ and $p_n\\geq 2n+1$. Prize: no. Tags: number theory.","id":"vf_437f692d0e63f437","trust":"signed","type":"theoretical"},{"assertion":"AI-contributions wiki claim — wiki: Candidate partial result (solutions to first part and second part; conditional solution to third part).","id":"vf_991c56adaafbbcf6","trust":"signed","type":"theoretical"}],"accepted_activity":false,"activity":[],"activity_types":[],"attempt_count":0,"banked_attempt_count":0,"commits":[],"dependency_impact":"none","detail_url":"problems/456.json","draft_proposals":[],"edges":[{"evidence":"Problem identity derived from the accepted finding's pinned source anchor.","inferred":true,"relation":"describes","source":"vf_124f1d0f80706e80","source_root":"sha256:d3db36661e28b7570fc8704bf8455b80d8382beded47d069f2c386144d90a238","target":"erdos:456","trust":"signed"},{"evidence":"Materialized typed link between accepted findings.","inferred":true,"relation":"synthesized_from","source":"vf_124f1d0f80706e80","source_root":"sha256:d3db36661e28b7570fc8704bf8455b80d8382beded47d069f2c386144d90a238","target":"vf_437f692d0e63f437","trust":"signed"},{"evidence":"Problem identity derived from the accepted finding's pinned so